  "reading": "Independent confirmation that minimal double blocking sets of size 3q−1 exist in PG(2,q) — smaller than the trivial 3q triangle and, for prime q > 13, the first known below 3q — refuting R. Hill's 1984 expectation that none with two (q−1)-secants exist. From the points printed in the paper, Leibniz reconstructs each set and verifies by exact GF(q) incidence arithmetic, over the five prime cases q ∈ {13,19,31,37,43}, that every one of the q²+q+1 lines meets it in ≥ 2 points (double blocking) and that every point lies on a 2-secant (minimality), reproducing the paper's published secant distribution exactly in each case. The Lean 4.31 kernel re-decides both properties, plus a discriminating negative control, for q = 13 and q = 19 (plain decide; every theorem depends on no axioms; no native_decide, no sorry). Exact arithmetic + the kernel; no LLM judgment; no trust surface."
